@article{Miller1990,
abstract = {Person-positivity bias is a tendency for people to evaluate individuals more positively than the groups they compose. Two experiments were conducted to test the hypothesis that person-positivity bias would occur only in evaluations of disliked people. Results showed, as expected, that individuals were not evaluated more positively than the groups they composed when the people being evaluated were physically attractive (Experiment 1) or were described as having likable personalities (Experiment 2). Person-positivity bias did occur when the people being evaluated were low in physical attractiveness (Experiment 1) or were described as having unlikable personalities (Experiment 2). The hypothesis that perceived similarity accounts for person-positivity bias was supported only in Experiment 2. The hypothesis that person-positivity bias is an example of a set-size effect was not supported. Discussion suggests that person-positivity bias may counteract some of the negative effects of stereotypes. ?? 1990.},
